725328f-a.text:
(1)
10-14 Forty-first Ave., north side, east of Main Street, showing the Wright property from 1873 to 1898. Eugene L. Armbruster states that in 1837 the Wright house stood on the north side of Madison Street (now Forty-first Ave.) at the corner of Main Street . However, in 1893, the two buildings at the corner were owned by C.H. Hurst while
the next two were owned by W. Wright.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
The same, showing a rear view.
1922.
Eugene L. Armoruster Collection.

727321f-a.text:
Main Street at Forty-first Avenue, showing two views looking eastward from the Main Street elevated station of the Long Island Railroad. At the left of the station in both views are the remains of the Flushing Institute. The spire at the right background of both views is that of St. Michael's R.C. Church. The peaked roof house in view No. 2 beyond the awning and shade sign
is the Wright house on Forty-first Avenue.
February 24, 1925.
Views 1 and 2
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
